                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=dasprid",
                        "name": "dasprid",
                        "displayName": "Ben Scholzen",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Interesting, didn't know that. Do you have an idea how to recognize the window width? Else I'll google around a bit myself.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=dasprid",
                        "name": "dasprid",
                        "displayName": "Ben Scholzen",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-10-01T17:06:11.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-10-01T17:06:11.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/35058",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=falkon",
                        "name": "falkon",
                        "displayName": "R S",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Unfortunatelly I don't have any idea :(\nBut maybe you can try find information also about Windows PowerShell - more sophisticated shell than cmd. I think, it could offer some way, how to obtain window size, and maybe there could be some reference, how it is possible (or impossible) to get window size also for cmd window. ",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=falkon",
                        "name": "falkon",
                        "displayName": "R S",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-10-02T13:19:47.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-10-02T13:19:47.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/36562",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=robertbasic",
                        "name": "robertbasic",
                        "displayName": "Robert Basic",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "When cmd.exe is started, you can type \"mode con\" which will give something like:\r\n{code}\r\nMicrosoft Windows XP [Version 5.1.2600]\r\n(C) Copyright 1985-2001 Microsoft Corp.\r\n\r\nC:\\Documents and Settings\\Robert>mode con\r\n\r\nStatus for device CON:\r\n----------------------\r\n    Lines:          300\r\n    Columns:        80\r\n    Keyboard rate:  31\r\n    Keyboard delay: 1\r\n    Code page:      437\r\n\r\n\r\nC:\\Documents and Settings\\Robert>\r\n{code}\r\nThe \"Columns\" is the screen buffer height and the \"Lines\" is the screen buffer width.\r\n\r\nOne can change those two values by executing something like:\r\n{code}\r\nmode con: lines=20 cols=50\r\n{code}\r\nthis is only for the active window only and for the active session only, e.g., default values will be used on next startup. Also, when this is executed, the scrollbar is gone and the window resize\/maximize feature is not working.\r\n\r\nIf you want to execute \"mode con\" right on cmd.exe's startup, run it like:\r\n{code}\r\ncmd.exe \/k mode con\r\n{code}\r\n\r\nReferences:\r\nhttp:\/\/commandwindows.com\/configure.htm\r\nhttp:\/\/stackoverflow.com\/questions\/190543\/changing-the-width-of-a-windows-console-window",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=robertbasic",
                        "name": "robertbasic",
                        "displayName": "Robert Basic",
                        "active": true
                    },
